lexicon.long: Aaron, son of Amram and Jochebed, brother of Moses.
Abel, second son of Adam and Eve, brother of Cain.
Abiathar, a priest in King David's time.
Abijah, (a) a king, son of Rehoboam, (b) founder of the eighth class of priests.
Abraham, progenitor of the Hebrew race.
Adam, the first man, the first parent of the human race.
Ahaz, son of Jotham and father of Hezekiah.
Andrew, brother of Simon Peter, and one of the apostles of Jesus, belonging to Bethsaida.
Anna, a prophetess, who visited the infant Jesus.
Annas, high priest at Jerusalem.
an Antiochian, an inhabitant of Antioch.
Antioch, (a) Antioch on the river Orontes, capital of the Province Syria, (b) "Pisidian" Antioch, not in Pisidia, but near Pisidia, in the Roman Province Galatia.
Apollos, a Jew of Alexandria.
the Greek way of writing the Latin Aquila, a male proper name; the husband of Priscilla (Prisca), and a Jew, of a family belonging to (Sinope in ?) Pontus.
Arabia, the district south of Palestine.
an Arabian.
Asa, son of Abijah and father of Jehoshaphat, king of Judah about 900 B.C. for 41 years.
Asher, one of the sons of Jacob, and founder of one of the Twelve Tribes.

lexicon.brief: roughly the western third of Asia Minor
lexicon.long: the Roman province of Asia, roughly the western third of Asia Minor.
Baal, chief deity of the Phoenicians and other Semitic nations.
(a) Babylon, the ancient city on the Euphrates, to which the people of Jerusalem, etc., were transported, (b) hence allegorically of Rome, from the point of view of the Christian people.
Balaam, son of Beor of Pethor on the Euphrates, a soothsayer in the Old Testament.
Barabbas.
Barnabas, a Cypriote Jew, uncle of John Mark; his other name was Joseph.
Joseph, a proper name.
Bartholomew, surname of Nathanael, one of the twelve apostles of Jesus.
Beelzebul, a name of Satan, the chief of evil spirits.
Benjamin, youngest son of Jacob, founder of one of the twelve tribes of Israel.
Berea, a town of the province Macedonia.
belonging to Berea, Berean.
(a) Bethany, the home of Lazarus, Martha, and Mary, near Jerusalem, (b) Bethany, beyond Jordan.
Bethlehem, a town of Judea.
Boaz, son of Salmon and Rahab, husband of Ruth, father of Obed.
Boaz, son of Salmon and Rahab, husband of Ruth, father of Obed.
Caesar, a surname of the gens Iulia, which became practically synonymous with the Emperor for the time being; in the Gospels it always refers to Tiberias.
(official Greek equivalent of Augustus), venerated, august, a title of the Roman emperors; hence secondarily: Augustan, imperial.
Two cities of Palestine: one in Galilee (Caesarea Philippi), the other on the coast of the Mediterranean.
Caiaphas, Jewish high priest.
(Hebrew), Cain, son of Adam and Eve and brother of Abel.
Cana, a town in Galilee.
Canaan, the whole of Palestine or Palestine west of the river Jordan.
Canaanite, a Biblical and archaic name for Phoenician.
Capernaum, a town of Galilee.
a Chaldean.
Cilicia, a Roman province between the Taurus range of mountains and the coast in the south-east corner of Asia Minor, linked up with the province of Syria.
Colossae, a town of the Roman province Asia, in the Lycus valley, near Laodicea and Hierapolis.
Corinthian, of Corinth.
Corinth, in north-east Peloponnese, the capital of the Roman province Achaia.
Cornelius, a centurion of the Roman army, stationed at Caesarea.
Crete.
a Cretan, an inhabitant of Crete.
a Cypriote, belonging to Cyprus.
Cyprus.
Cyrene, a district west of Egypt on the Mediterranean coast, forming with Crete a Roman province.
belonging to Cyrene, a Cyrenaean.
Damascus.
Daniel.
David, King of Israel.
Idumea, Edom, a district of Arabia, immediately south of Judea.
Egyptian.
Egypt.
an Elamite, one of a people living to the north of the Persian Gulf in the southern part of Persia.
Eleazar, son of Eliud, and father of Matthan.
Eliakim, son of Abiud and father of Azor; son of Melea and father of Jonam.
Elijah, the prophet.
Elisha.
Elizabeth, mother of John the Baptizer.
Enoch, son of Jared and father of Methuselah.
Ephesian, of Ephesus.
Ephesus, a coast city, capital of the Roman province Asia.
Ephraim, a city.
Esau, elder son of Isaac the patriarch, brother of Jacob.
an Ethiopian, Abyssinian.
the Euphrates, boundary river of the province Syria.
Eve, the first woman; wife of first man Adam.
the angel Gabriel, a messenger of God.
Gad, one of the twelve tribes of Israel.
a Galatian (meaning any inhabitant of the Roman province Galatia).

Galatia, a large Roman province in central Asia Minor, comprising the districts of Paphlagonia, Pontus Galaticus, Galatia (in the narrower sense, which some still think is intended in the NT), Phrygia Galatica, Lycaonia Galatica, Pisidia and Isaurica.
Galatic, belonging to the province Galatia.
Galilee, a district towards the southern end of the Roman province Syria; the northern division of Palestine.
a Galilean, an inhabitant of Galilee.
Gaza, an old town in the south of Palestine, on the sea-coast.
Gethsemane, a small place between the brook Kidron and the Mount of Olives near Jerusalem.
Gideon, one of the Judges of Israel.
Golgotha, a knoll outside the wall of Jerusalem.
Gomorrah, one of the destroyed cities on the Dead Sea.
Hellas, the native name for Greece.
a Hellene, the native word for a Greek; it is, however, a term wide enough to include all Greek-speaking (i.e. educated) non-Jews.
a female Greek.
Greek, the Greek language.
a Hellenist, Grecian Jew, a Greek-speaking Jew, that is one who can speak Greek only and not Hebrew (or Aramaic).
in the Greek language.
Hagar, the servant of Sarah, concubine of Abraham.
Haran.
Herod; four persons are called by this name: Herod the Great, Herod Antipas, Herod Agrippa, and Herod Agrippa the younger.
Herodias (died after A.D. 40), daughter of Aristobulus and granddaughter of Herod I, wife, first, of her uncle Herod, second, of his half-brother, her uncle Herod Antipas.
Hezekiah, son of Ahaz, father of Manasseh, and king of Judah (727-686 [?] B.C.).
Hosea, the Hebrew prophet.
Iconium, a Phrygian city of the Roman province Galatia (modern Konia).
(Hebrew), Isaac, the patriarch.
Isaiah, the prophet.
Issachar, a proper name.
(Hebrew), Jacob, (a) the patriarch, son of Isaac, (b) father of Joseph, the husband of Mary.
James, (a) the Small, son of Alphaeus, and one of the Twelve, (b) half-brother of Jesus, (c) father (?) of Jude, (d) son of Zebedee, and brother of John, one of the Twelve, killed A.D. 44.
(Hebrew), Joram, Jehoram, son of Jehoshaphat and father of Uzziah.
(Hebrew), Jehoshaphat, king of Judah, son of Asaph, father of Joram, an ancestor of Jesus.
(Hebrew), Jephthah, one of the Judges of Israel.
Jeremiah, Hebrew prophet.
Jericho, a city a little north of the Dead Sea.
the Greek form of the Hebrew name: Jerusalem.
an inhabitant of Jerusalem.
the Greek form of the Hebrew name: Jerusalem.
(Hebrew), Jesse, son of Obed, and father of King David.
Jezebel, name given to a false prophetess of Thyatira, possibly borrowed from the name of Ahab's wife, queen of Israel.
(Hebrew), Job, the hero of the book of that name in the Old Testament.
Mark, who also had the Hebrew name John, son of Mary, nephew of Barnabas, coadjutor of Barnabas, Paul, and Peter.
John: the Baptist, the apostle, a member of the Sanhedrin, or John Mark.
(Hebrew), Jonah, the Hebrew prophet.
Joppa, a coast town of Judea, west-north-west of Jerusalem.
the Jordan, a great river flowing due south and bounding Galilee, Samaria, and Judea on the east.
Jesus; the Greek form of Joshua; Jesus, son of Eliezer; Jesus, surnamed Justus.
(Hebrew), Josiah, king of Judah.
Jotham, son of Uzziah and father of Ahaz.
Judah, Judas, Jude.
Iscariot, surname of Judas.
Judea, a Roman province, capital Jerusalem.
Jewish.
(Hebrew) Korah.
(Hebrew), Lamech, son of Methuselah and father of Noah.
Lazarus, Eliezer, (a) the beggar, (b) the brother of Martha and Mary, of Bethany.
a Levite, properly a man of the tribe of Levi; hence: a priest's assistant, an under priest, as the members of that tribe were charged with this duty.
belonging to the tribe of Levi; Levitical.

(Hebrew), Levi, (a) an ancestor of Jesus, (b) another ancestor of Jesus, (c) third son of Jacob, the patriarch, and founder of a tribe named after him, (d) son of Alphaeus, and called Matthew, a revenue officer and one of the twelve apostles of Jesus.

(Hebrew), Levi, (a) an ancestor of Jesus, (b) another ancestor of Jesus, (c) third son of Jacob, the patriarch, and founder of a tribe named after him, (d) son of Alphaeus, and called Matthew, a revenue officer and one of the twelve apostles of Jesus.
(Hebrew), Lot, nephew of Abraham.
Lucas, Luke, Christian physician and writer of the Third Gospel and Acts.
Lystra, a Lycaonian city in the southern part of the Roman province Galatia.
(Hebrew), Macedonia, a Roman province north of Achaia (Greece).
a Macedonian, an inhabitant of the Roman province Macedonia.
(Hebrew), Manasseh, (a) son of Joseph, founder of a tribe of Israel, (b) son of Hezekiah and father of Amon (Amos).
Martha, sister of Mary and Lazarus of Bethany.
Mary, Miriam, (a) the mother of Jesus, (b) of Magdala, (c) sister of Martha and Lazarus, (d) wife of Cleopas, (e) mother of John Mark, (f) a Christian woman in Rome.
Mary, Miriam, (a) the mother of Jesus, (b) of Magdala, (c) sister of Martha and Lazarus, (d) wife of Cleopas, (e) mother of John Mark, (f) a Christian woman in Rome.
Matthew.
a Mede, a Median, from east of Assyria.
(a) the sea, in contrast to the land, (b) a particular sea or lake, e.g. the sea of Galilee (Tiberias), the Red Sea.
Melchizedek, king and priest of Salem.
Mesopotamia, the Country between the (two) Rivers, i.e. the Euphrates and the Tigris.
Michael, an archangel.
(Hebrew), Midian, generally taken to mean or to include the peninsula of Sinai.
Moloch, a god worshipped by several Semitic peoples.
Moses; met: the books of Moses, the Pentateuch.
Naaman.
Nahor, one of the ancestors of Jesus.
Naphtali, son of Jacob, founder of a tribe which occupied territory.
Nathan, son of David, and an ancestor of Jesus.
Nazareth, a city of Galilee, where Jesus lived before His ministry.
Nazareth, a city of Galilee, where Jesus lived before His ministry.
Nazareth, a city of Galilee, where Jesus lived before His ministry.
of Nazareth, a Nazarene.
a Nazarene, an inhabitant of Nazareth.
a Ninevite, an inhabitant of Nineveh, a city on the Tigris in Assyria.
(Hebrew) Noah.
Paul, Paulus.
Saul, the apostle.
Saul, the apostle.
Cephas (Aramaic for rock), the new name given to Simon Peter, the apostle.
Peter, a Greek name meaning "rock".
Simon.
Simeon or Simon.
Pharaoh, the title of ancient Egyptian kings.

Philip, (a) one of the twelve apostles of Jesus, (b) tetrarch of the Ituraean and Trachonitic region, half-brother of Herod Antipas, tetrarch of Galilee, (c) one of the seven original deacons at Jerusalem and a missionary.
Philippi, a great city of the Roman province Macedonia.
a Philippian, an inhabitant of Philippi.
Phoenicia, a northern coast strip of the Roman province Syria.
Pilate.
belonging to Pontus.
Pontus, a Roman province in the north of Asia Minor, bordering on the Black Sea, governed along with Bithynia.
Prisca, Priscilla, the former being the more correct and formal name, the latter a diminutive and more familiar; a Roman lady, probably of good birth, wife of the Jewish Christian Aquila.
Prisca, Priscilla, the former being the more correct and formal name, the latter a diminutive and more familiar; a Roman lady, probably of good birth, wife of the Jewish Christian Aquila.
Rachel, younger wife of the patriarch Jacob.
Rahab, a Canaanitess, who rescued the Hebrew spies at Jericho.
Rahab, a Canaanitess, who rescued the Hebrew spies at Jericho.
Rama, a place in Ephraim, two hours north of Jerusalem.
Rebecca, wife of the patriarch Isaac.
Rehoboam, son of Solomon, and King of Israel.
Reuben, eldest son of the patriarch Jacob and founder of a tribe.
Roman; subst: a Roman citizen.
Rome, the famous city on the Tiber, the capital of the Roman Empire.
Ruth, wife of Boaz and mother of Obed.

Samaria, a small district of Palestine, bounded by Galilee on the north, and by Judaea on the south, and taking its name from the city of Samaria, the ancient capital of the kingdom of (northern) Israel.
a Samaritan.
a Samaritan woman.
Samson, one of the Judges of Israel.
Samuel, a Hebrew prophet.
Sarah, wife of Abraham.
a lake.
Seth, third son of Adam.
Shechem.
Shem, a son of Noah.
Sidonian, inhabitant of Sidon.
Sidon, a great coast city of Phoenicia.
Silvanus, a Roman citizen and a helper of Paul.
Silas, a pet-form of the name "Silvanus"; a Roman citizen and a helper of Paul.
Silas, a pet-form of the name "Silvanus"; a Roman citizen and a helper of Paul.
Sodom.
Solomon, son of David King of Israel, and Bathsheba.
Solomon, son of David King of Israel, and Bathsheba.
Stephen, one of the seven original deacons at Jerusalem, and the first martyr.
Syria, a great Roman imperial province, united with Cilicia.
Syrian, belonging to Syria.
Tamar, mother of Perez and Zerah by Judah, son of Jacob.
belonging to Tarsus, a Tarsian.
Tarsus, the capital of the Roman province Cilicia.
Terah, the father of Abraham.
Thessalonica (modern Saloniki), an important city of the Roman province Macedonia.
a Thessalonian.
Thomas, also called Didymus, one of the Twelve.
Timothy, a Christian of Lystra, helper of Paul.
Titus, a Greek Christian, helper of Paul, perhaps also brother of Luke.
Troas, a harbor city of Mysia.
Tychicus, a Christian of the Roman province Asia.
a Tyrian, an inhabitant of Tyre.
Tyre, an ancient city, the capital of Phoenicia.
Uriah, husband of Bathsheba the mother of Solomon.
Uzziah, son of Joram and father of Jotham, and king of Judah from about 785 to 746 B.C., an ancestor of Jesus.
Zacchaeus, a Jewish tax-gatherer.
Zadok, an ancestor of Jesus.
Zebedee, father of the apostles James and John.
Zebulon, one of the sons of Jacob, and founder of one of the twelve tribes.
Zechariah, (a) a priest referred to as a son of Jehoiada, (b) another priest, father of John the Baptist.
Zerubbabel, son of Shealtiel (Salathiel) and father of Abiud and Rhesa.
